[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] Sphinx is a *documentation generator* or a tool that translates a set of plain text source files into various output formats, automatically producing cross-references, indices, etc.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] That is, if you have a directory containing a bunch of reStructuredText or Markdown documents, Sphinx can generate a series of HTML files, a PDF file (via LaTeX), man pages and much more.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] Sphinx focuses on documentation, in particular handwritten documentation, however, Sphinx can also be used to generate blogs, homepages and even books.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] Much of Sphinx’s power comes from the richness of its default plain-text markup format, reStructuredText, along with its significant extensibility capabilities.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] The goal of this document is to give you a quick taste of what Sphinx is and how you might use it.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] When you’re done here, you can check out the installation guide followed by the intro to the default markup format used by Sphinx, reStructuredText.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] For a great “introduction” to writing docs in general – the whys and hows, see also Write the docs, written by Eric Holscher.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] The root directory of a Sphinx collection of plain-text document sources is called the source directory.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] Sphinx comes with a script called **sphinx-quickstart** that sets up a source directory and creates a default `conf.py` with the most useful configuration values from a few questions it asks you.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] Let’s assume you’ve run **sphinx-quickstart**.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] It created a source directory with `conf.py` and a root document, `index.rst`.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] The main function of the root document is to serve as a welcome page, and to contain the root of the “table of contents tree” (or *toctree*).
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] This is one of the main things that Sphinx adds to reStructuredText, a way to connect multiple files to a single hierarchy of documents.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] `toctree` is a reStructuredText *directive*, a very versatile piece of markup.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] Directives can have arguments, options and content.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] A common gotcha with directives is that **the first line of the content must be indented to the same level as the options are**.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] This is exactly how the `toctree` for this documentation looks.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] The documents to include are given as document names, which in short means that you leave off the file name extension and use forward slashes (`/`) as directory separators.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] You can now create the files you listed in the `toctree` and add content, and their section titles will be inserted (up to the `maxdepth` level) at the place where the `toctree` directive is placed.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] Also, Sphinx now knows about the order and hierarchy of your documents.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] In Sphinx source files, you can use most features of standard reStructuredText.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] There are also several features added by Sphinx.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] For example, you can add cross-file references in a portable way (which works for all output types) using the `ref` role.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] For an example, if you are viewing the HTML version, you can look at the source for this document – use the “Show Source” link in the sidebar.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] reStructuredText for a more in-depth introduction to reStructuredText, including markup added by Sphinx.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] Now that you have added some files and content, let’s make a first build of the docs.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] where *sourcedir* is the source directory, and *outputdir* is the directory in which you want to place the built documentation.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] The `-M` option selects a builder; in this example Sphinx will build HTML files.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] Refer to the sphinx-build man page for all options that **sphinx-build** supports.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] You can also build a **live version of the documentation** that you can preview in the browser.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] It will detect changes and reload the page any time you make edits.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] However, **sphinx-quickstart** script creates a `Makefile` and a `make.bat` which make life even easier for you.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] These can be executed by running **make** with the name of the builder.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] This will build HTML docs in the build directory you chose.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] Execute **make** without an argument to see which targets are available.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] `make latexpdf` runs the `LaTeX builder` and readily invokes the pdfTeX toolchain for you.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] One of Sphinx’s main objectives is easy documentation of *objects* (in a very general sense) in any *domain*.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] A domain is a collection of object types that belong together, complete with markup to create and reference descriptions of these objects.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] The most prominent domain is the Python domain.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] For example, to document Python’s built-in function `enumerate()`, you would add this to one of your source files.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] Return an iterator that yields tuples of an index and an item of the *sequence*.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] The argument of the directive is the *signature* of the object you describe, the content is the documentation for it.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] Multiple signatures can be given, each in its own line.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] The Python domain also happens to be the default domain, so you don’t need to prefix the markup with the domain name.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] does the same job if you keep the default setting for the default domain.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] There are several more directives for documenting other types of Python objects, for example `py:class` or `py:method`.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] There is also a cross-referencing *role* for each of these object types.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] This markup will create a link to the documentation of `enumerate()`.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] And here is the proof: A link to `enumerate()`.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] Again, the `py:` can be left out if the Python domain is the default one.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] It doesn’t matter which file contains the actual documentation for `enumerate()`; Sphinx will find it and create a link to it.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] Each domain will have special rules for how the signatures can look like, and make the formatted output look pretty, or add specific features like links to parameter types, e.g. in the C/C++ domains.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] Domains for all the available domains and their directives/roles.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] Earlier we mentioned that the `conf.py` file controls how Sphinx processes your documents.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] In that file, which is executed as a Python source file, you assign configuration values.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] For advanced users: since it is executed by Sphinx, you can do non-trivial tasks in it, like extending `sys.path` or importing a module to find out the version you are documenting.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] The config values that you probably want to change are already put into the `conf.py` by **sphinx-quickstart** and initially commented out (with standard Python syntax: a `#` comments the rest of the line).
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] To change the default value, remove the hash sign and modify the value.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] To customize a config value that is not automatically added by **sphinx-quickstart**, just add an additional assignment.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] Keep in mind that the file uses Python syntax for strings, numbers, lists and so on.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] The file is saved in UTF-8 by default, as indicated by the encoding declaration in the first line.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] Configuration for documentation of all available config values.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] When documenting Python code, it is common to put a lot of documentation in the source files, in documentation strings.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] Sphinx supports the inclusion of docstrings from your modules with an *extension* (an extension is a Python module that provides additional features for Sphinx projects) called *autodoc*.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] `sphinx.ext.autodoc` for the complete description of the features of autodoc.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] Many Sphinx documents including the Python documentation are published on the Internet.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] When you want to make links to such documents from your documentation, you can do it with `sphinx.ext.intersphinx`.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] In order to use intersphinx, you need to activate it in `conf.py` by putting the string `'sphinx.ext.intersphinx'` into the `extensions` list and set up the `intersphinx_mapping` config value.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] And now, you can write a cross-reference like :py:func:`io.open`.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] Any cross-reference that has no matching target in the current documentation set, will be looked up in the documentation sets configured in `intersphinx_mapping` (this needs access to the URL in order to download the list of valid targets).
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] Intersphinx also works for some other domain's roles including `:ref:`, however it doesn’t work for `:doc:` as that is non-domain role.
[src:sphinx-docs/quickstart] `sphinx.ext.intersphinx` for the complete description of the features of intersphinx.
[src:sphinx-docs/read-the-docs] The site was created in 2010 by Eric Holscher, Bobby Grace, and Charles Leifer.
[src:sphinx-docs/read-the-docs] On March 9, 2011, the Python Software Foundation Board awarded a grant of US$840 to the Read the Docs project for one year of hosting fees.
[src:sphinx-docs/read-the-docs] On November 13, 2017, the Linux Mint project announced that they were moving their documentation to Read the Docs.
[src:sphinx-docs/read-the-docs] In 2020, Read the Docs received a $200,000 grant from the Chan Zuckerberg Initiative.
[src:sphinx-docs/read-the-docs] For 2021, Read the Docs reported 700 million page views and 196 million unique visitors.
[src:sphinx-docs/read-the-docs] In 2013, a "Write the Docs" conference for Read the Docs users was launched, which has since turned into a generic software-documentation community.
[src:sphinx-docs/sphinx-documentation-generator] Sphinx converts reStructuredText files into HTML websites and other formats including PDF, EPub, Texinfo and man.
[src:sphinx-docs/sphinx-documentation-generator] reStructuredText is extensible, and Sphinx exploits its extensible nature through a number of extensions – for autogenerating documentation from source code, writing mathematical notation or highlighting source code, etc.
[src:sphinx-docs/sphinx-documentation-generator] It is possible to use Markdown files as well thanks to extensions such as MyST Parser.
[src:sphinx-docs/sphinx-documentation-generator] Sphinx provides the ability to apply themes to HTML and HTML-based formats.
[src:sphinx-docs/sphinx-documentation-generator] Sphinx has several built-in themes, including alabaster, classic, sphinxdoc, and scrolls.
[src:sphinx-docs/sphinx-documentation-generator] The first public release, version 0.1.61611, was announced on March 21, 2008.
[src:sphinx-docs/sphinx-documentation-generator] It was developed for, and is used extensively by, the Python project for documentation.
[src:sphinx-docs/sphinx-documentation-generator] Since its introduction in 2008, Sphinx has been adopted by many other important Python projects, including Bazaar, SQLAlchemy, MayaVi, SageMath, SciPy, Django and Pylons.
[src:sphinx-docs/sphinx-documentation-generator] It is also used for the Blender user manual and Python API documentation.
[src:sphinx-docs/sphinx-documentation-generator] In 2010, Eric Holscher announced the creation of the Read the Docs project as part of an effort to make maintenance of software documentation easier.
[src:sphinx-docs/sphinx-documentation-generator] Read the Docs automates the process of building and uploading Sphinx documentation after every commit.
[src:sphinx-docs/sphinx-documentation-generator] The Linux kernel's documentation subsystem underwent changes in 2016.
[src:sphinx-docs/sphinx-documentation-generator] Starting in the 4.7 cycle, the documentation started switching over to use Sphinx.
[src:sphinx-docs/tutorial-index] In this tutorial you will build a simple documentation project using Sphinx, and view it in your browser as HTML.
[src:sphinx-docs/tutorial-index] The project will include narrative, handwritten documentation, as well as autogenerated API documentation.
[src:sphinx-docs/tutorial-index] The tutorial is aimed towards Sphinx newcomers willing to learn the fundamentals of how projects are created and structured.
[src:sphinx-docs/tutorial-index] You will create a fictional software library to generate random food recipes that will serve as a guide throughout the process, with the objective of properly documenting it.
[src:sphinx-docs/tutorial-index] To showcase Sphinx capabilities for code documentation you will use Python, which also supports *automatic* documentation generation.
[src:sphinx-docs/tutorial-index] Several other languages are natively supported in Sphinx for *manual* code documentation, however they require extensions for *automatic* code documentation, like Breathe.
[src:sphinx-docs/tutorial-index] To follow the instructions you will need access to a Linux-like command line and a basic understanding of how it works, as well as a working Python installation for development, since you will use *Python virtual environments* to create the project.
